The service was almost like a choreographed dance routine. I definitely think this place is the best restaurant in SF!

Gary Danko was my first Michelin star restaurant. I heard that it was one of the best restaurants in SF, so I decided to indulge my taste buds. Attentive servers, elegant ambiance and delicious food is how I would sum up my experience. I chose 4 courses (crispy farm egg, scallop, duck and steak) with a glass of Cabernet Sauvignon. At the time, it was the best meal I have ever had, but now my standards have been raised after touring other Michelin star restaurants in the Bay Area. Definitely plan on coming back sometime soon.

I heard a lot about this place and I came with pretty high expectations. More of a place for couples. I loved the caviar and the seafood was good (ordered the lobster). I recommend this place for a date. Enjoy some cocktails and a nice dinner.

Was it worth it to splurge on fine dining at Gary Danko? Absolutely!! It took me 2 months to make reservations and the food and ambiance definitely lived up to the hype. Upon arriving, I was instantly greeted by friendly staff who quickly sat us to our table. We were given a complimentary small bite size appetizer to start things off, as well as, bread. I recommend getting the 4 course meal because I was soo full by the end of the meal. My BF, on the other hand, got the 5 course meal and was overly stuffed as well. In addition to the dessert I ordered with my meal, the restaurant also provided complimentary assortment of small candies and cookies. Lastly, Gary Danko also gives you a banana cake gift to take home with you! The only critique I have for this place is that all the tables are closely seated together. Other than that, I had a wonderful experience.

My heart goes out to the poor girl on her terrible date seated next to us. The seating here is pretty intimate so our table heard more than we wanted from her loud mouthed and slightly perverted date, who, btw, didn't even pay Come on, buddy! You can't expect to get any if you're stingy. Anyway, the service here is great but at times felt a little overwhelming. Susan covered our table and she did a great job recommending dishes, orders or dishes, wines...basically she's what you'd expect from a good waitress/waiter. Foie gras was tender with a nice bite to it. The dish was paired with slices of peach and some caramelized onions that really completed the dish. Lobster salad was...okay. I personally wouldn't order this again, not that it was disgusting, it was just a little boring to me. The vinaigrette tasted a bit too much like mayo though the fennel did go nicely with the lobster. Salmon medallion was overcooked. Pork belly and tenderloin was really great. Both were cooked perfectly and had nice flavors it it even without the sauce. The potato-sorrel puree the pork belly was sitting under was so yummy and buttery. Actually, I think I would've preferred the belly to be served with the veggies and the tenderloin to be served with the puree to balance things out a bit. Braised veal and pistachio crusted sweetbreads was good and bad. The veal was overcooked so I left it alone. The sweetbreads were so good, I wish it came on a dish on its own. The crust was nice contrast in texture; it was crunchy but not too hard. Trio of creme brulee was good. They had good chocolate/lemon/vanilla flavors it but I personally liked the original the most. They all had a nice, crunchy , and burned top. Souffle was good, but the sauce that it was served with was even better. Now there was one more dessert that was really really good. I'm not sure what it's even called being that it wasn't on the menu. While I was choosing my dishes I asked the waitress about a passion fruit dessert . I skimmed some reviews on yelp prior and remembered someone raaaaving about it. The waitress tells me that they don't so I move a long and finish my order. Anyway, the waitress shows up at the end of the meal with the passion fruit dessert. Turns out it is only served for celebrations and the waitress said it was a celebration bc it was our first time there. Woohoo! Overall, a good experience.

tl;dr: food was pretty good, service was pretty bad. We reserved two months in advance (we wanted 8pm on a Saturday night!). It was off to a slow start; our table wasn't ready until about 8:15 and the bar was too busy for us to wait there, so we stood awkwardly in the entrance. No matter, though, they checked my husband's dinner jacket (though didn't ask me about mine?) and seated us in a corner table, which was nice. The feel is fancy, in a stuffy formal way, but I enjoy that from time to time. We wore dinner jackets, shirt and slacks. No ties. Generally the crowd was business casual attire, which works for us. The food was overall good, however inconsistent. My fried egg with grits, pancetta, and frisee was a nice appetizer, and I marveled that they deep fried an egg without coking the yolk. The grits were over salted (you have to season knowing it will cook down and intensify), but had a good, thick texture. In my second course, the bass was overcooked (dry!) and underseasoned, but the gnocchi it came with were some of the best I've ever had. The pork tenderloin and cheeks were cooked perfectly, though the plating was a bit messy. The jus was a very rich pan sauce, which is good since the tenderloin had a mild flavor. My husband's duck was good, with a similar preparation to my pork. His dish came with a duck hash that was mushy and too salty, unfortunately. Dessert! I couldn't help but order the chocolate souffle. They poke a hole and pour in creme anglaise and chocolate sauce. It was as light as aerogel, but unfortunately too delicate in texture and flavor for me. My husband's beignets with coffee pot de creme, however, were wonderful. I ended up eating most of both, since he was too full. As we started our dessert courses, they brought out some little treats (mignardises?) that were excellent, though I wish they had come after the dessert course... Which is why the rating is so low: BAD SERVICE. The food is worthy of a solid 4 stars, but the service was comically bad. The main source of our problems was the waiter, Seamus. I can be obnoxious, but my husband is very nice and polite. Yet Seamus was not nice at all to him. No attempt to recommend dishes to us. I had put the wine list down on the table, and when my husband asked if there were any non-alcoholic drinks, he just said, "on page 5" and walked away. At a decent restaurant, the waiter might wait for you to peruse the half dozen options and pick one, and at a good restaurant the waiter would pick up the book from the table, open it to the appropriate page, and hand it to you. I asked for a glass of wine for my first two courses and said I would choose a red later for my meat course. As it turns out, the meat course (3rd course) was down in front of me before I saw Seamus again. He hustled over to ask if I wanted a glass of something for my pork and did not recommend one. My husband's first drink was done and gone by this point as well, so he ordered another from memory, since we no longer had a drink menu at hand. Props where they're due, both wines were excellent, and one of my husband's two drinks was very good. We were twice given sliced bread at room temperature. Butter was fridge-cold and thus impossible to spread. (They did stamp a lovely waffle design on the top, though.) The first three courses came out blazingly fast, in fact we arrived at 7:55, sat at 8:15 and had our main dish in front of us by 9. Which meant we were too full halfway through that course to really enjoy it. We did not see Seamus again after the mid-third-course drink ordering until we were ready for the check. Ironically, even though the courses came too fast, we ended up getting impatient after finishing dessert. The table was cleared and we had our napkins on the table for 20 minutes before we saw our waiter for the fourth and final time -- just to ask if we wanted the check. I don't think we have ever felt so unwelcome at an upscale restaurant. We won't be going back.

San Francisco Food Fantasy Trip... take three. Ok... so the Mrs. and I planned a 3 day trip to San Francisco... let's see... what's on the list... Golden Gate Bridge, Alcatraz, the Wharf??? NOPE.. this is a food only trip. No tourist stuff here.. no time for that.... JUST FOOD, FOOD, and more FOOD... plus 12 hours of sleep to take breaks between the food. ZAGAT... best restaurant in San Francisco. Highest Yelp honors in San Francisco. Summary -- "Diners select from three, four or five prix-fixe menu courses. Danko's signature dishes include roast Maine lobster with white corn, tarragon and chanterelles, pancetta wrapped frog legs with garlic purée, and roasted quail stuffed with mushrooms and foie gras. Most dishes are served year round, but ingredients are adjusted seasonally to emphasize local produce. In late spring, Danko's seared foie gras is paired with Bing cherries, but in early fall, with roast figs." Wearing jeans and my Green Day American Idiot concert tour 2007 t-shirt, the Wife and I were ready for our take it or leave it, balls to the wall, all out dinner... the elusive Gary Danko... 5 star best of the best food in the Bay Area. Located about two blocks from the infamous Ghirardelli ice cream chaos center, this place is easy to find. We enter and are greeted by the hostess... immediately I notice everyone and their mother is wearing full on suits, ties, nice shiny shoes... the hostess takes a few looks at me...up and down... my Green Day t-shirt proudly shining in the mood-lit ambiance. Ok.. so I felt a little out of place... but hey, if they want my $$$ they shouldn't have a problem with it. I don't. I'm on vacation, I'm not putting on a suit and tie.... Are you high?... Anyway.. the important part... The meal. As summarized, you pick from either a 3,4, or 5 course dinner.. $65, $85, and $98 per person.... We both opted for the 4 course dinner... the 5th course was really just some cheese... eh... I could do without cheese. Course 1: Wife "Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing" wife - it was ok.. nothing special... me - have to agree.. it was good though don't get me wrong... but nothing special. Course 1: Me "Lobster and Fennel Bisque with Dungeness Crab, Peppers and Saffron-Orange Rémoulade" oooh soo good. Wow... good thing I chose this. Wife thought it was a little too sweet... but I thought it was awesome. Course 2: Wife "Coconut Thai Curry with Lemongrass, Calamari, Lobster, Scallions and Shiitake Mushrooms" eh... poor choice by the Mrs... Curry wasn't bad.. but I could eat this at any Thai restaurant. Course 2: Me "Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon" WOW... WOW.. WOW.. probably the best lobster I've ever had.. and the potato puree that accompanied it... oooh.. sooo good. My mouth died and went to heaven. The Wife should have ordered this also... man... I just lost of my dish. Course 3: Wife "Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras, Mushrooms and Quinoa, Cornbread Pudding, Roma Beans, Bacon and Tomato-Corn Relish" Wife thought this was too salty.. especially the stuffing... I on the other hand thought it was pretty darn good. And the Cornbread Pudding... soo good. Awe.. life is good. Course 3: Me "Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Ramp Purée, Peas, Bacon, Pickled Onions and Maple Glaze" Another winner for me... so so so good. Perfectly glazed on the outside... tender tender tender on the inside... Course 4: Wife "Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Caramelized Apricots, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream" eh... it was ok.. another bad choice for the Mrs. Course 4: Me "Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces" I love me a good soufflé... now this wasn't anything special.. and not the best I've ever had... but it was a good and I did lick my bowl dry... Overall... Price is what you expect for a top of the line kind of place. Service was impeccable... ambiance was perfect for that intimate setting... food... the food ranged from good to oh my god I just wet my pants... I think they had a few misses... but for the most part the food was realy really good. Larger than normal for this kind of restaurant portions also helped.. I left full and happy... and still wearing my Green Day American Idiot tour 2007 t-shirt with pride.

There really isn't much I can say that other people haven't already said, but I'll try to put in my two cents. The experience can be summed up in a few words = WARM & IMPECCABLE SERVICE + COMFORT FOOD at its best. I was pretty excited when I found out the bf had made reservations here for my birthday, but boy, was I in for a real treat!!! By the end of the night, I had decided this was definitely one of the top places for me in the city. We were seated at the bar for about 15-20 minutes while we waited for our seats. Our reservations were at 10 and it seemed the restaurant was running a little behind. During our wait, though, they brought us some complimentary sparkling wine which was delicious and we had a great conversation with the bartender. They seated us in a table where we sat next to each other - something I absolutely love!!! It's so much more intimate to have a conversation with someone that way. While we were examining the menu for our top choices, they also brought us some chili to try and a buttery, flaky tart with salmon on top. Both were absolutely delicious and I couldn't wait to start ordering our dishes! We decided to go with the risotto with lobster, which was amazingly creamy and probably had a stick of butter in it, but I didn't even care, it was THAT GOOD. The lobster was also perfectly cooked. Next was the scallops. Both were seared & seasoned to perfection. The sauce underneath was DIVINE. For someone who thinks scallops is a hit or miss item, this was a homerun dish. We then had the other lobster dish, which sat on top of the creamiest potatoes ever. The bf couldn't stop raving about how it was the best mashed potato he ever had. The meat dishes that night consisted of the lamb and pork belly & pork loin. Both were delicious, but a bit on the salty side for me. This was probably not a huge issue since I was already so full, I had to leave the boy to do the cleanup work. The meal then ended with a complimentary passion fruit cake (?) for my birthday. It was SOOOO YUMMY, I couldn't stop eating it and smiling, then eating and smiling some more. The service staff at GD is absolutely amazing and they make you feel like you're one of their frequent guests. Can't say enough good things about them! Thanks GD & pang for the amazing birthday meal :)

    8/3/2013

    tl;dr: food was pretty good, service was pretty bad.

    We reserved two months in advance (we wanted 8pm on a Saturday night!). It was off to a slow start; our table wasn't ready until about 8:15 and the bar was too busy for us to wait there, so we stood awkwardly in the entrance. No matter, though, they checked my husband's dinner jacket (though didn't ask me about mine?) and seated us in a corner table, which was nice. The feel is fancy, in a stuffy formal way, but I enjoy that from time to time.

    We wore dinner jackets, shirt and slacks. No ties. Generally the crowd was business casual attire, which works for us.

    The food was overall good, however inconsistent. My fried egg with grits, pancetta, and frisee was a nice appetizer, and I marveled that they deep fried an egg without coking the yolk. The grits were over salted (you have to season knowing it will cook down and intensify), but had a good, thick texture. In my second course, the bass was overcooked (dry!) and underseasoned, but the gnocchi it came with were some of the best I've ever had.

    The pork tenderloin and cheeks were cooked perfectly, though the plating was a bit messy. The jus was a very rich pan sauce, which is good since the tenderloin had a mild flavor. My husband's duck was good, with a similar preparation to my pork. His dish came with a duck hash that was mushy and too salty, unfortunately.

    Dessert! I couldn't help but order the chocolate souffle. They poke a hole and pour in creme anglaise and chocolate sauce. It was as light as aerogel, but unfortunately too delicate in texture and flavor for me. My husband's beignets with coffee pot de creme, however, were wonderful. I ended up eating most of both, since he was too full. As we started our dessert courses, they brought out some little treats (mignardises?) that were excellent, though I wish they had come after the dessert course...

    Which is why the rating is so low: BAD SERVICE. The food is worthy of a solid 4 stars, but the service was comically bad. The main source of our problems was the waiter, Seamus. I can be obnoxious, but my husband is very nice and polite. Yet Seamus was not nice at all to him. No attempt to recommend dishes to us. I had put the wine list down on the table, and when my husband asked if there were any non-alcoholic drinks, he just said, "on page 5" and walked away. At a decent restaurant, the waiter might wait for you to peruse the half dozen options and pick one, and at a good restaurant the waiter would pick up the book from the table, open it to the appropriate page, and hand it to you.

    I asked for a glass of wine for my first two courses and said I would choose a red later for my meat course. As it turns out, the meat course (3rd course) was down in front of me before I saw Seamus again. He hustled over to ask if I wanted a glass of something for my pork and did not recommend one. My husband's first drink was done and gone by this point as well, so he ordered another from memory, since we no longer had a drink menu at hand. Props where they're due, both wines were excellent, and one of my husband's two drinks was very good.

    We were twice given sliced bread at room temperature. Butter was fridge-cold and thus impossible to spread. (They did stamp a lovely waffle design on the top, though.)

    The first three courses came out blazingly fast, in fact we arrived at 7:55, sat at 8:15 and had our main dish in front of us by 9. Which meant we were too full halfway through that course to really enjoy it.

    We did not see Seamus again after the mid-third-course drink ordering until we were ready for the check. Ironically, even though the courses came too fast, we ended up getting impatient after finishing dessert. The table was cleared and we had our napkins on the table for 20 minutes before we saw our waiter for the fourth and final time -- just to ask if we wanted the check.

    I don't think we have ever felt so unwelcome at an upscale restaurant. We won't be going back.

    San Francisco Food Fantasy Trip... take three.  Ok... so the Mrs. and I planned a 3 day trip to San Francisco... let's see... what's on the list... Golden Gate Bridge, Alcatraz, the Wharf??? NOPE.. this is a food only trip.  No tourist stuff here.. no time for that.... JUST FOOD, FOOD, and more FOOD... plus 12 hours of sleep to take breaks between the food.

    ZAGAT... best restaurant in San Francisco.  Highest Yelp honors in San Francisco.  Summary -- "Diners select from three, four or five prix-fixe menu courses. Danko's signature dishes include roast Maine lobster with white corn, tarragon and chanterelles, pancetta wrapped frog legs with garlic purée, and roasted quail stuffed with mushrooms and foie gras. Most dishes are served year round, but ingredients are adjusted seasonally to emphasize local produce. In late spring, Danko's seared foie gras is paired with Bing cherries, but in early fall, with roast figs."

    Wearing jeans and my Green Day American Idiot concert tour 2007 t-shirt, the Wife and I were ready for our take it or leave it, balls to the wall, all out dinner... the elusive Gary Danko... 5 star best of the best food in the Bay Area.   Located about two blocks from the infamous Ghirardelli ice cream chaos center, this place is easy to find.  We enter and are greeted by the hostess... immediately I notice everyone and their mother is wearing full on suits, ties, nice shiny shoes... the hostess takes a few looks at me...up and down... my Green Day t-shirt proudly shining in the mood-lit ambiance.  Ok.. so I felt a little out of place... but hey, if they want my $$$ they shouldn't have a problem with it. I don't.  I'm on vacation, I'm not putting on a suit and tie.... Are you high?... Anyway.. the important part...

    The meal.
    As summarized, you pick from either a 3,4, or 5 course dinner.. $65, $85, and $98 per person.... We both opted for the 4 course dinner... the 5th course was really just some cheese... eh... I could do without cheese.
    Course 1: Wife
    "Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms and Lemon Soy Dressing"  wife - it was ok.. nothing special... me - have to agree.. it was good though don't get me wrong... but nothing special.

    Course 1: Me
    "Lobster and Fennel Bisque with Dungeness Crab, Peppers and Saffron-Orange Rémoulade"  oooh soo good.  Wow... good thing I chose this.  Wife thought it was a little too sweet... but I thought it was awesome.

    Course 2: Wife
    "Coconut Thai Curry with Lemongrass, Calamari, Lobster, Scallions and Shiitake Mushrooms"  eh... poor choice by the Mrs... Curry wasn't bad.. but I could eat this at any Thai restaurant.

    Course 2: Me
    "Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon" WOW... WOW.. WOW.. probably the best lobster I've ever had.. and the potato puree that accompanied it... oooh.. sooo good.  My mouth died and went to heaven.  The Wife should have ordered this also... man... I just lost  of my dish.

    Course 3: Wife
    "Quail Stuffed with Foie Gras, Mushrooms and Quinoa, Cornbread Pudding, Roma Beans, Bacon and Tomato-Corn Relish"  Wife thought this was too salty.. especially the stuffing... I on the other hand thought it was pretty darn good.  And the Cornbread Pudding... soo good.  Awe.. life is good.

    Course 3: Me
    "Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Ramp Purée, Peas, Bacon, Pickled Onions and Maple Glaze"  Another winner for me... so so so good.  Perfectly glazed on the outside... tender tender tender on the inside...

    Course 4: Wife
    "Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Caramelized Apricots, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream"  eh... it was ok..  another bad choice for the Mrs.

    Course 4: Me
    "Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces"  I love me a good soufflé... now this wasn't anything special.. and not the best I've ever had... but it was a good and I did lick my bowl dry...

    Overall... Price is what you expect for a top of the line kind of place.  Service was impeccable... ambiance was perfect for that intimate setting... food... the food ranged from good to oh my god I just wet my pants...  I think they had a few misses... but for the most part the food was realy really good.  Larger than normal for this kind of restaurant portions also helped.. I left full and happy... and still wearing my Green Day American Idiot tour 2007 t-shirt with pride.

    -ROASTED PORK BELLY and Tenderloin with Potato-Ramp PurÈe, Fava Beans, Artichokes and Maple Glaze (Again, EXPLOSION of flavor and perfectly cooked.)
    -SEARED FILET OF BEEF with Yukon Potatoes, Curried Cauliflower, Cumin-Cilantro Butter and Tamarind Glaze (The filet was juicy, tender, and it paired so well with everything else on the plate.)
    -LEMON PEPPER DUCK BREAST with Duck Hash, Carrot-Ginger PurÈe and Vanilla Poached Rhubarb (Every bite on the plate, each time was a taste of something amazingly different, SO GOOD!)
    -QUAIL STUFFED WITH FOIE GRAS with Mushrooms, Artichokes, Olives and Scallion-Potato Cake (It looked like a cute little mini turkey on my plate:) You can't really taste or find an actually piece of foie gras. It was still really good, but again....a little bit on the salty side.)
    -BAKED CHOCOALATE SOUFFLÈ with Two Sauces (I've had better, a bit too mushy for my liking. However, the sauces were delicious!)
    -TRIO OF CREME BRULÈE with Assorted Cookies (Chocolate, Butterscotch, and classic....Best ever, creamy, not too sweet, and to die for! I wanted it all in and around my mouth, it was THAT good!)

    COMPLIMENTARY GOODIES:
    I guess they give everybody complimentary goodies, but  felt like we got the whole sha-bang of goodies!
    -AMUSE BOUCHE (Great little opener of Cauliflower soup to tantalize your taste buds.)
    -PETIT DESSERT PLATE ( Mini little brownie, maccaroon, lemon bar, lemon tart, chocolate tarte, and etc. I wish they sold these!)
    -PINEAPPLE BLUEBERRY BREAKFAST MUFFIN (For the day after, DUH! I've never had a restaurant give me something for the day after!?!?)
    -CHAMPAGNE (For 6 of us! Perfect bubbly for a perfect evening!)
    -DECADENT CHOCOLATE CAKE ( I know everyone gets complimentary goodies here on their bday, but....a cake that would be able to serve 12 people??? Amazing, I tell ya!)

    So overall, yes it was the BEST RESTAURANT EXPERIENCE and FOOD! I would defnitely come back her for the SEARED FOIE GRAS, ROAST MAINE LOBSTER, SEARED SCALLOPS, TRIO OF CREME BRULEE, AND SERVICE!

    THANK YOU GARY DANKO FOR A MEMORABLE BIRTHDAY! :D
